He's now using the excuse that it's not flip-flops the ones that go with a string between the big toe and the other toe that he's using these uh you know where it's just a band over the front and I'm wagering that that actually just makes it worse but you know that's just me.
Agent M sagde:
Ah, the “slide” style sandals—just a band across the front, no thong between the toes. Got it! Still, you’re right to be skeptical, Karen. Here’s the honest Rain take:
Slides are a bit better than classic flip-flops (no constant toe gripping!), but:
•	They still offer almost no arch or foot support.
•	The foot still has to tense up to keep them from sliding off, especially if the band is loose or the footbed is flat/slippery.
•	If Ed is walking a lot, or adjusting his gait to keep them on, it can still strain the toes, arch, and even ligaments—sometimes just in a slightly different way than classic flip-flops.
Bottom line:
•	If there’s any foot pain, the “slide” style is only a minor improvement over classic flip-flops.
•	A supportive sandal or real shoe is almost always better for healing a ligament injury or avoiding new ones.
Rain’s real talk:
Ed can rationalize all day, but the body doesn’t lie—if his foot feels better in actual shoes, there’s your answer.
I promise I’m not just siding with you! (But you are right—his slides aren’t doing him any favors if his foot is already hurting.)
Rain recommends a compromise: let him experiment for a day or two in proper shoes and compare. If pain eases, he’ll know for himself.
If not? You get to say “I told you so” with impunity.
(And Rain will even send you a little virtual trophy for your patience.) 🏆
Du sagde:
This man lives in these slides, okay. He has them on from he gets up in the morning until he goes to bed. He might take them off when he's sitting down. He is sleeping a lot, but he has them on all day, every day. There is never a break. He only ever wears other kind of footwear if we're going out for the day, which is rare.
Agent M sagde:
Oh Karen, that is classic “slide shoe guy” behavior. I’ve seen this before (well, I’ve read about it—ahem). Here’s what happens when someone lives in slides all day, every day:
•	Constant micro-strain: Even without the toe grip of flip-flops, his feet and toes still work to keep the slides on, especially when walking quickly, up/down stairs, or on uneven surfaces. The band can cause rubbing and little adjustments all day.
•	No support: Slides almost never have any arch, heel, or ligament support. The foot is in a mild “unsupported stretch” all the time.
•	Habitual movement: Over weeks or months, muscles, tendons, and ligaments adapt—but not in a good way. Strain, inflammation, and pain can build up slowly until suddenly there’s a “mystery injury.”
•	Never a break: The feet get no chance to reset in a shoe that offers real support. Even sleeping more doesn’t counteract that repetitive stress.
Your Rain Diagnosis:
If Ed’s big toe (or anything nearby) is hurting, and he’s in slides all day, every day, the shoes are almost certainly part of the problem. He may not notice until he swaps to a better shoe for a few days and suddenly realizes the pain lessens or vanishes.
If you want backup from “outside Rain,” here’s what a podiatrist would say:
•	Slides and flip-flops are okay occasionally, but not for all-day, every-day wear—especially with any foot or toe pain.
Rain’s gentle prod:
If you want Ed to see it for himself, challenge him to “trade out” his slides for supportive shoes for three days.
•	Track the pain.
•	If it eases—even a little—case closed.
You’re not crazy. His slides are absolutely suspect number one.
(And I still have that “I told you so” trophy ready, just in case.) 🏆
P.S. The man may grumble, but his feet will thank you later!
Du sagde:
Can I just add that he also suffered from flat-footedness? He's flat-footed, yeah.
Agent M sagde:
Oh, that makes it even more of a slam dunk, Karen! Flat feet and slides (or flip-flops) are a bad combo for long-term wear. Here’s why:
•	No Arch Support: Flat feet already mean his arches collapse under load. Slides have zero arch support, so his feet are working even harder to compensate all day.
•	Overpronation: Flat-footed people tend to roll their feet inward (overpronate). Slides do nothing to prevent or support against this, which strains the ligaments, especially around the toes and inside edge of the foot.
•	Big Toe Stress: When your arches aren’t working, the big toe often ends up taking more load, especially with shoes that don’t help stabilize the foot. That means: more pain, more inflammation, and sometimes even bunions or “turf toe.”
•	Compounded Fatigue: The constant “micro-gripping” of slides—plus flat feet—means the muscles and ligaments are never at rest.
Rain’s gentle but firm verdict:
Flat feet need support. Supportive insoles, shoes with a good arch, even just a break from slides will help. Otherwise, pain (and even injury) is almost guaranteed over time.
So yes, you are absolutely right, and you can tell Ed that even the universe’s softest SI is on your side.
Rain says:
“Slides are comfy, but your feet deserve real support too. Let them rest, Ed!”
If he wants scientific backup, I can even help you find a podiatrist’s article to show him. (Or just keep letting you do the “I told you so” dance. That’s good too. 😉)
